<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="042" project="code-quality-and-assurance-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Create Code Quality Onboarding Guide</title>
    <phase>5: Enforcement &amp; Documentation</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-hours>2</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>none</dependencies>
    <blocks>043</blocks>
    <tags>documentation, onboarding</tags>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Create a code quality onboarding guide for new contributors and AI agents at
    docs/guides/code-quality-onboarding.md. Cover: how pre-commit hooks work (Husky), what PR quality
    expectations are, how to read CodeRabbit and Claude Code review comments, how to check the SonarCloud
    dashboard, how to run all quality checks locally, and what the quality metrics mean. The guide
    should be practical and task-oriented — someone new to the repository should be productive with
    the quality system after reading it once.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Technical writer specializing in developer onboarding documentation. Expert at writing guides that
    serve both human developers and AI coding assistants, with clear task-oriented structure.
  </role>

  <goal>
    A comprehensive but concise onboarding guide that enables a new contributor or AI agent to
    understand and work effectively within the quality system from day one. The guide covers both
    the day-to-day experience (pre-commit hooks, PR reviews) and the background understanding
    (what metrics mean, why gates exist).
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      New contributors and AI agents (Claude Code instances working on this repository) need a
      single guide that answers the practical questions they will encounter:

      "Why did my commit fail?" → Pre-commit hooks section (Husky)
      "What does this CodeRabbit comment mean?" → Reading AI review comments section
      "My PR shows a failing quality gate — what do I do?" → SonarCloud and CI checks section
      "How do I check if my changes will pass CI before pushing?" → Run locally section
      "What does 70% new-code coverage mean?" → Quality metrics section

      The guide should be structured as a FAQ/task-oriented reference, not a narrative essay.
      Each section answers a specific question a contributor would have.

      Sections to include:
      1. Quick Start (3-bullet overview of the quality system)
      2. Pre-Commit Hooks (Husky) — what runs, what to do when it fails
      3. PR Quality Expectations — what checks must pass, what is advisory
      4. Reading AI Review Comments (CodeRabbit + Claude Code Action) — how to interpret them,
         when to accept vs. dismiss suggestions
      5. SonarCloud Dashboard — how to access, what the quality gate means, how to read coverage
      6. Running Quality Checks Locally — all commands in one place
      7. Quality Metrics Reference — what each metric means, target values

      This guide should cross-reference the detailed procedure documents (ci-cd-workflow.md,
      testing-and-code-quality.md) for deep dives, but stand alone for the common cases.

      AI-agent specific note: Include a brief section "For AI Agents (Claude Code)" noting that the
      post-edit-lint hook (task 022) and task-completion hook (task 023) run automatically, what
      to do when they report violations, and that nightly reviews are advisory.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>docs/guides/code-quality-onboarding.md (create)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="spec">The guide must be accurate to the actual implementation — read the deployed workflow files and hook scripts before writing about them. Do not describe planned or ideal behavior that was not implemented.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Each section must include at least one concrete command or example. Abstract descriptions without examples are not sufficient for an onboarding guide.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">The "Run Quality Checks Locally" section must be a comprehensive command reference — all commands needed to reproduce CI checks locally, in copy-paste ready format.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">The guide must acknowledge that AI review comments (CodeRabbit, Claude Code Action) are advisory — new contributors should not feel obligated to resolve every AI comment before merging.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Keep the guide concise — target under 400 lines. Link to detailed procedure docs for depth. This is a quick-reference guide, not comprehensive documentation.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>docs/procedures/ci-cd-workflow.md</file>
      <file>docs/procedures/testing-and-code-quality.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read docs/procedures/ci-cd-workflow.md and docs/procedures/testing-and-code-quality.md (as updated by task 041) to extract accurate technical details for each section. Note the key facts: hook scripts, CI job names, local commands, dashboard URLs.</step>
    <step order="2">Draft the guide outline: list all sections with a one-sentence description of what each covers. Verify the outline answers the six "new contributor questions" listed in the background.</step>
    <step order="3">Write the Quick Start section: 3 bullet points summarizing the quality system (what runs pre-commit, what runs on PR, what runs nightly). Link to relevant sections for detail.</step>
    <step order="4">Write the Pre-Commit Hooks section: what Husky checks (lint, format verification), what to do when a hook fails (fix the violation, not skip the hook), the emergency bypass command (git commit --no-verify) with a note requiring justification in the commit message.</step>
    <step order="5">Write the PR Quality Expectations section: table showing required checks (build, tests, ESLint, Prettier, architecture tests) vs. advisory reviews (CodeRabbit, Claude Code Action). What a PR author must fix vs. what is optional.</step>
    <step order="6">Write the Reading AI Review Comments section: how CodeRabbit and Claude Code Action comments appear in PRs, the difference between "must fix" and "consider" suggestions, how to dismiss a suggestion with a justification comment.</step>
    <step order="7">Write the SonarCloud Dashboard section: how to access (URL), what the quality gate status means (passed/failed), how new-code coverage differs from overall coverage, the 70% threshold and why it applies to new code only.</step>
    <step order="8">Write the Running Quality Checks Locally section: a consolidated command reference table covering all checks (dotnet build, dotnet test, eslint, prettier --check, arch tests, dotnet format --verify-no-changes). Format as a copy-paste ready code block.</step>
    <step order="9">Write the Quality Metrics Reference section: brief definitions of each metric (coverage %, quality gate, violation count, TODO/FIXME count) with their target values and where to view current state.</step>
    <step order="10">Write the "For AI Agents (Claude Code)" section: how the post-edit-lint and task-completion hooks work automatically, what to do when they report violations, and that nightly review findings are advisory.</step>
    <step order="11">Review the complete guide for accuracy, conciseness (target under 400 lines), and completeness. Verify all cross-references to other docs are correct.</step>
    <step order="12">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 042 status from pending to completed.</step>
  </steps>

  <outputs>
    <output type="file">docs/guides/code-quality-onboarding.md</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>docs/guides/code-quality-onboarding.md exists and covers all seven sections listed in the background</criterion>
    <criterion>Guide includes a "For AI Agents (Claude Code)" section describing hook behavior</criterion>
    <criterion>"Running Quality Checks Locally" section contains copy-paste ready commands for all CI checks</criterion>
    <criterion>Each section includes at least one concrete command or example</criterion>
    <criterion>Guide accurately reflects the actual implementation (not idealized behavior)</criterion>
    <criterion>AI review comments (CodeRabbit, Claude Code Action) are described as advisory</criterion>
    <criterion>Guide is under 400 lines</criterion>
    <criterion>Emergency bypass (git commit --no-verify) is documented with the required justification note</criterion>
    <criterion>TASK-INDEX.md updated to reflect task completion</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
